I listened to the following program on ABC Radio National recently: THE SOCIAL INTELLIGENCE HYPOTHESIS (Science Show: 17/02/2007)http://www.abc.net.au/rn/scienceshow/stories/2007/1846476.htm

It had the following precis: "Why do humans have such large brains? How did they get to be so large? The human brain had two large growth spurts. About 2 million years ago it increased by 50%, then a few hundred thousand years ago it increased again. This week on The Science Show, Wendy Barnaby traces the history of the human brain and looks at the social intelligence hypothesis which suggests being able to get along with each other, understand each other and each other's thoughts led to one of the big increases in the size of the human brain."

The main thesis of the program seemed to be that  about 2 million years ago brain size increased because people were living in larger more complex groups, and were having to keep track of different people and a larger number of social relationships. Apparently there was another growth spurt about 200,000 years ago, when language developed.

What bothers me is the idea that brain size increased to allow these developments. It seems as though the argument is that some of our ancestors sat round the camp fire, perhaps as a committee, and decided that their offspring would need larger brains to cope with social developments, so they obliged in some way. I would have thought that these developments followed the increase in brain size, if, indeed, an increase in brain size was needed for them to take place.

What is it with brain size, anyway? Birds have relatively tiny brains, but some species are capable of feats of navigation that humans require a suite of electronic equipment to perform. *pink This is a REALLY REALLY REALLY good point ... and navigation is the least of it.  Birds, especially if you pick the most intelligent birds as your examples, such as large parrots and corvids (crows, magpies, currawongs etc.), are much more intelligent than almost any mammals in almost every way, even though their brains are tiny.  I can tell stories in class about this if you remind me.  Somehow, birds' brains are much more efficient than ours.*

*pink But still there is something important about brain size.  I guess changes in brain efficiency are very rare, since they must require really major mutations.  In that case, evolutionary changes will often pit species with similar brain efficiencies but different brain sizes against each other.  Jason*

As I said, I really know very little about this subject, but, secure in my ignorance, I feel uncomfortable with what I perceive to be the teleological implications of the social intelligence hypothesis.

Get out the slings and arrows folks. Attack me. Tell me why I'm wrong. I'm seeking enlightenment.

*green But you're not wrong!  Jason*

Dick Parker

