 This is always a tricky question. It's a bit like the one with the bat's sonar and their large ears. If the sonar came first, it would have been useless without the finely tuned hearing, but if the hearing came first, what caused it to develop?

From what I understand (which isn't neccessarily a lot, I admit), maybe the larger groups came together for reasons that had little to do with brain size- for better protection from predators, for example. Then perhaps those with slightly larger brains- or rather brains with a slightly different structure, had the advantage in dealing with the situation, and a better chance of mating. With regard to the language part of the question, maybe again our brain size and the complexity of our language grew side by side, beginning with very simple signs, once our throats had changed to allow speech. Which leaves us with the question of why our throats changed in the first place- I have no idea, so if anyone does know, please fill us in.

Lastly, with regard to brain size and language, from what I remember from an essay done long, long ago, there is a theory that there is a particular part of the brain devoted to complex language, and that our possession of this is the reason that we are able to form complex sentances, etc, while chimps can understand and use only simpler signs; 'bannana', but not 'please give me a bannana'. So perhaps comprehension of language has more to do with brain mechanisms than brain size.

-Jess Nelson

-----

It's certainly true that brain 'mechanisms' have functional evolutionary priority over sheer brain size. One stark illustration is that homo neanderthalensis (Neanderthals, european species of advanced hominid ) had a signficantly larger brain, judging from skull capacities, than we do, but were nowhere near as psychologically complex, shown basically by the fact that they were wiped out by our ancestors when they walked into europe around 35-30kya. *green I don't see why psychological complexity should always win.  Please explain (maybe in class). Jason* Another way of thinking about it is that more complex mechanisms tend to require more meat. *green Ahem ... or vegetables.  Jason* But it's no strict law: my understanding is that even homo sapiens brains have actually shrunk over the evolutionary recent past. Brains are expensive to run, so getting better efficiency with less meat is going to be favourable.

The chicken-egg problems of how such complex and deeply situational traits got to be there at all are at the heart of the big questions in bioanth about human evolution, as I assume it is in all evolution science. It's also what creationists latch onto in order to claim irreducible complexity. But you can, with enough evidence, really create plausible sounding theories to (try to) explain these things. It's all about narrating a chain of happy unions of potentials and pressures, selection for one trait involving a side effect that is then selected for with respect to some other trait or niche. Society makes it more complicated as well, because social interactions are not clearly either traits or niches but kind of both. 

There is a DVD at the (now somewhat wrecked, it seems!) library about human evolution, but it's pretty rubbish., people in apesuits, totally overdramatic and far too slow. If anyone is interested I could have a go at explaining some of the {pre-XX, should say:} non-social pressures and potentials in early hominids. I wont just start recanting because, well, it's a long story. but very interesting. though i'm sure there are enough guides-to on the net...

- Tom

