You're right, complexity wont always win. I've been wondering recently whether a metaphysics of complexity could say anything about this, but I can't think of any basis for it being in any sense necessary. But so far as biology is concerned, in certain concrete forms complexity has and continues to win. *blue In hominins(#!), yes.  In general, I don't think so, but I guess you don't mean in general. Jason*

{Another nice analytic re-statement of what evolution just is about!}

I guess my specific point about the neanderthals should be qualified to something like this. Both neanderthals and homosapiens relied utterly on their unique behavioural complexities. not exclusively; neanderthals were much more suitably built to survive the -30degree European iceage winters. But even despite this relative disadvantage sapiens drove them out. notably, before the end of glaciation. Whether by violence or by competition for resources doesn't matter, they evidently possessed an adaptive complexity that allowed them to move their hairless and lithe bodies in a few thousand years out of the middle eastern deserts into the articwastes, pushing the chunky rivals into extinction. We can also point to the fact that only homosapiens had proper art, had much more sophisticated tool tech etcetc. No simple 'smartness', but surely complexity nonetheless, and one that surely was/ is some substantial ground of homosapiens' success. *blue Yes.*

re meat, I meant in that instance *red brainmeat*, hardware. *blue Ah!*

but your point is a good criticism anyway: we could've eaten more plants to get the extra energy needed, so I should have been more careful. though then we would need to explain why they started to eat more plants - larger brains? the chicken-egg situation again, or rather brain-foodenergy. 

as I understand it the way this particular theory deals with the problem is to say that the early hominiNs*red #* who started to eat meat, mostly scavenged, especially bone marrow accessed with stone tools, got with the same gut more energy out per energy used to digest, meaning that they were able to develop both shorter guts (less invested there) and larger brains (more invested there). why they started to eat meat is tricky too, but it seems implausible to say that they moved to meat in response to energy needs from bigger brains. apart from the fact that we'd then have to explain the brainexpansion somehowelse, it's also relevant that some chimps are similarly omnivorous and use many different tools,despite having comperably sized brains to these scavenging ancestors.

