Re brain size in birds: It is probable that birds, flying as most do, were (and are) under substantial pressure to be streamlined, balanced and light i.e. to have small brains (among other things). As to how they achieve complex neural feats with relatively small brains, I suspect the answer has at least two parts. 

Firstly, ‘It’s not the size that counts’ a popular phrase that women would do well to remember, as it is the basis for the assertion that ‘men aren’t smarter than women’. Studies (just search google scholar) have indicated that connections between brain hemispheres and also neurons per unit-volume and synapses (in certain areas) tend to be more numerous in women than in men. These studies offer possible, partial explanation of how women manage to match men, in undertaking numerous complex neural feats, despite having smaller brains (generally speaking). If smaller, more densely connected brains can work as efficiently as larger, less densely connected brains; one can imagine that bird species would be under substantial pressure favouring any mutants who carried genes that added brain function without increasing size, or that maintained brain function but reduced necessary brain size. (…and being called ‘dense’ would be a good thing.)

Secondly, I have read that the brain anatomy of birds is fundamentally different than that of mammals in many ways so, regardless of density, they may have evolved a more compact way of achieving some complex feats. Perhaps more likely is that birds have evolved the capacity to achieve some complex neural feats, however their range of such feats is limited to an extent that relates to their brain size.

I am wondering though, if birds are under such pressure to have small, light heads; where did pelicans come from? Check out the beak on those things! Talk about a character that would be ambivalent to selection; can being able to have ‘take-away’ be that beneficial?

In the scheme of things, mutations that increase brain-efficiency may not be that unlikely. If a brain is more efficient for its size when more highly interconnected, then a mutation that reduced the neuronal thinning (which occurs in developing brains) might be enough to affect an efficiency increase. The process of neural apoptosis (programmed cell death) could be controlled by easily disrupted, and relatively simple mechanisms.

Hamish.
